## JavaScript Data Types (Deep Dive)

Data types define what kind of values a variable can hold and how those values behave — they determine how data is stored in memory and how operations like comparison, calculation, and conversion work.

---

### Primitive Data Types
Primitive types represent simple, immutable values stored directly in memory.

#### 1. Number
Covers both integers and floating-point numbers. Special values include `Infinity`, `-Infinity`, and `NaN` (for computational errors).
```js
let a = 42;          // integer
let b = 3.14;        // float
let c = Infinity;    // special value
let d = "abc" / 2;   // NaN
```

#### 2. String
A series of characters surrounded by quotes. Three types of quotes are supported.
```js
let s1 = "Double quotes";
let s2 = 'Single quotes';
let s3 = `Template literal — embed: ${s1}`;  // backticks
```

#### 3. Boolean
```js
let t = true;
let f = false;
```

#### 4. Null
`null` does not belong to any default data type — it forms its own separate type. It represents nothing, or an empty value.
```js
let age = null;  // intentionally empty
```

#### 5. Undefined
A variable that has been declared but not initialized is automatically assigned `undefined`. It means the variable exists but has no value.
```js
let a;
console.log(a);  // undefined
```

#### 6. Symbol *(ES6)*
Symbols are unique and immutable primitive values used as identifiers for object properties. They help create unique keys in objects, preventing conflicts.
```js
let s1 = Symbol("id");
let s2 = Symbol("id");
console.log(s1 == s2);  // false — always unique
```

#### 7. BigInt *(ES2020)*
`BigInt` represents whole numbers greater than `2^53` (beyond `Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER`).
```js
let big = 123456789012345678901234567890n;  // note the 'n' suffix
```

---

### Non-Primitive Data Types
Non-primitive types are derived from primitive types, also called reference data types.

#### 1. Object
Objects are key-value pairs used to store data, created with `{}` or the `new` keyword. Nearly everything in JavaScript is an object.
```js
let user = { name: "Ajay", age: 25 };
console.log(user.name);  // "Ajay"
```

#### 2. Array
A special kind of object used to store an ordered collection of values of any data type.
```js
let a1 = [1, 2, 3];
let a2 = [1, "two", { key: "val" }, [3, 4]];  // mixed types allowed
```

#### 3. Function
A block of reusable code designed to perform a specific task when called.
```js
function greet(name) { return "Hello, " + name; }
```

#### 4. Date Object
Used to work with dates and times, allowing for date creation, manipulation, and formatting.
```js
let now = new Date();
console.log(now);
```

#### 5. RegExp
An object used to define search patterns for matching text in strings.
```js
let pattern = /hello/;
pattern.test("Hello, world!");  // false — case sensitive
```

---

### Interesting Facts

**Dynamically Typed** — Variables are not bound to a specific data type. The type is stored with the value (not the variable name) and is decided at runtime.
```js
let x = 42;       // number
x = "hello";      // now a string
x = [1, 2, 3];    // now an array — all valid!
```

**Everything behaves like an Object** — Functions are objects, arrays are objects, and even primitives can temporarily behave like objects when you access properties on them (via a temporary wrapper).
```js
"hello".length      // 5
(42).toString()     // "42"
true.toString()     // "true"
```

**NaN is type `number`** — `NaN` stands for "Not-a-Number" and represents a computational error. It is technically of type `number`.
```js
typeof NaN       // "number"
NaN === NaN      // false — NaN is never equal to itself
```

**No `char` type** — There is no separate type for characters. A single character is also a string.
```js
typeof "g"    // "string"
typeof "gfg"  // "string"
```

**Integers and floats are the same type** — There is only one `number` type that covers both integers and floating-point numbers.
```js
typeof 42     // "number"
typeof 42.5   // "number"
```

---

### Quick Reference

| Type | Category | Example | `typeof` |
|---|---|---|---|
| Number | Primitive | `42`, `3.14`, `NaN` | `"number"` |
| String | Primitive | `"hello"` | `"string"` |
| Boolean | Primitive | `true` | `"boolean"` |
| Null | Primitive | `null` | `"object"` ⚠️ |
| Undefined | Primitive | `let x;` | `"undefined"` |
| Symbol | Primitive | `Symbol("id")` | `"symbol"` |
| BigInt | Primitive | `123n` | `"bigint"` |
| Object | Non-Primitive | `{}` | `"object"` |
| Array | Non-Primitive | `[]` | `"object"` |
| Function | Non-Primitive | `function(){}` | `"function"` |

> ⚠️ `typeof null` returns `"object"` — this is a well-known JS bug that was never fixed for backward compatibility.

