## Type Conversion & Type Coercion in JavaScript

JavaScript data types are flexible — the type of variables can change when the program runs. Type Conversion and Type Coercion are the two ways to change a variable's data type from one type to another.

---

### Type Conversion (Explicit)

Type Conversion is when the data type is converted manually by the programmer. It is also known as explicit type casting. It uses built-in JavaScript methods like `Number()`, `String()`, and `Boolean()`, giving full control over data types.

#### String → Number
Use `Number()`, `parseInt()`, or `parseFloat()`.

```js
Number("123")        // 123
Number("3.14")       // 3.14
Number("")           // 0
Number("abc")        // NaN
parseInt("42px")     // 42   — stops at first non-numeric char
parseFloat("3.14m")  // 3.14
```

#### Number → String
Use `String()` or concatenate with an empty string.

```js
String(123)    // "123"
(123).toString()  // "123"
123 + ""       // "123"
```

#### Boolean → Number
`true` becomes `1` and `false` becomes `0`.

```js
Number(true)   // 1
Number(false)  // 0
```

#### Boolean → String
Use `String()` or concatenate with an empty string.

```js
String(true)   // "true"
String(false)  // "false"
true + ""      // "true"
```

#### Other conversions to know
```js
Number(null)       // 0
Number(undefined)  // NaN
Number(true)       // 1
Number(false)      // 0
Boolean(0)         // false
Boolean("")        // false
Boolean(null)      // false
Boolean(undefined) // false
Boolean(NaN)       // false
Boolean("hello")   // true
Boolean(1)         // true
```

---

### Type Coercion (Implicit)

Type Coercion is the automatic conversion of one data type to another by JavaScript during operations. It is also known as implicit type casting. It happens mostly in comparison and arithmetic operations and can lead to unexpected results if not handled properly.

#### 1. String + Number → String
If a string is present in an arithmetic operation, JavaScript automatically converts the number to a string.

```js
5 + "5"      // "55"  ← number coerced to string
"5" + 3      // "53"
"5" - 3      // 2    ← string coerced to number (- doesn't concat)
"5" * 2      // 10
"10" / 2     // 5
```

> ⚠️ `+` with a string = concatenation. `-`, `*`, `/` always convert to number.

#### 2. Boolean + Number → Number
When performing arithmetic operations, JS converts `true` to `1` and `false` to `0`.

```js
true + 10    // 11
false + 10   // 10
true + true  // 2
```

#### 3. Comparison of Different Types
JavaScript converts the two values into a common type when comparing with `==`.

```js
"10" == 10     // true  — string coerced to number
0 == false     // true  — false coerced to 0
"" == false    // true  — both coerce to 0
null == undefined  // true  — special case
null == 0      // false — null only loosely equals undefined
```

#### 4. Boolean Context (Truthy / Falsy)
JavaScript converts non-boolean values to boolean when used in an `if` statement.

```js
// Falsy values — coerce to false
if ("")        // false
if (0)         // false
if (null)      // false
if (undefined) // false
if (NaN)       // false
if (false)     // false

// Truthy values — coerce to true
if ("hello")   // true
if (1)         // true
if ([])        // true  ← empty array is truthy!
if ({})        // true  ← empty object is truthy!
```

---

### Key Differences

| Feature | Type Conversion | Type Coercion |
|---|---|---|
| Performed by | Programmer | JavaScript Engine |
| Type | Explicit | Implicit |
| Control | Full control | Automatic |
| Example | `Number("5")` → `5` | `"5" - 2` → `3` |

---

### Tricky Coercion Examples

```js
[] + []        // ""    — both arrays convert to empty string
[] + {}        // "[object Object]"
{} + []        // 0     — {} treated as empty block, +[] = 0
"5" - - "3"   // 8     — both coerced to numbers
null + 1       // 1     — null becomes 0
undefined + 1  // NaN   — undefined becomes NaN
```

---

### Best Practices

Always use explicit type conversion where possible to avoid unexpected results. Use `===` instead of `==` to prevent unintended type coercion in comparisons. Convert inputs explicitly before performing operations. Use `typeof` to check data types before processing values.

```js
// Bad — relies on coercion
if (userInput) { ... }

// Good — explicit check
if (userInput !== "" && userInput !== null) { ... }

// Bad
"5" == 5   // true (coercion happens)

// Good
"5" === 5  // false (strict, no coercion)
```



