## JavaScript Control Flow Statements

Control flow statements control the order in which code is executed. They allow you to make decisions, repeat tasks, and jump between parts of a program based on specific conditions.

---

### 1. `if` Statement
Executes a block of code only if a specified condition is true.

```js
const age = 18;
if (age >= 18) {
    console.log("You are an adult.");
}
```

---

### 2. `if...else` Statement
Provides an alternate block of code to execute if the condition is false.

```js
const score = 40;
if (score >= 50) {
    console.log("You passed.");
} else {
    console.log("You failed.");
}
```

---

### 3. `if...else if...else` Statement
Used when you want to handle multiple conditions.

```js
const temp = 25;
if (temp > 30) {
    console.log("It's hot.");
} else if (temp >= 20) {
    console.log("It's warm.");
} else {
    console.log("It's cold.");
}
```

---

### 4. `switch` Statement
Evaluates an expression and executes a block of code based on matching cases. Provides an alternative to long if-else chains.

```js
const day = "Monday";
switch (day) {
    case "Monday":
        console.log("Start of the week.");
        break;           // ← always use break to stop fall-through
    case "Friday":
        console.log("End of the workweek.");
        break;
    default:             // ← runs if no case matches
        console.log("It's a regular day.");
}
```

> ⚠️ Without `break`, execution falls through to the next case!

**Fall-through (intentional use):**
```js
switch (day) {
    case "Saturday":
    case "Sunday":
        console.log("It's the weekend!");  // runs for both cases
        break;
}
```

---

### 5. Ternary Operator
Used to assign a value to a variable based on a condition. If the condition is true it returns the first value, otherwise the second.

```js
// Syntax: condition ? valueIfTrue : valueIfFalse

let a = 10;
console.log(a === 5 ? "a is 5" : "a is not 5");  // "a is not 5"

// Chained ternary (use sparingly)
let grade = score >= 90 ? "A" : score >= 70 ? "B" : "C";
```

---

### 6. Loops

#### `while` loop — checks condition BEFORE each iteration
```js
let i = 0;
while (i < 5) {
    console.log(i);
    i++;
}
// Runs only if condition is true from the start
```

#### `do...while` loop — checks condition AFTER each iteration
```js
let i = 0;
do {
    console.log(i);
    i++;
} while (i < 5);
// Always runs at least ONCE even if condition is false
```

---

### 7. All Types of `for` Loops

#### `for` — classic, index-based
```js
for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    console.log(i);   // 0 1 2 3 4
}

// Reverse loop
for (let i = 5; i >= 0; i--) {
    console.log(i);   // 5 4 3 2 1 0
}
```

#### `for...of` — iterates over VALUES of an iterable (array, string, set, map)
```js
const fruits = ["apple", "banana", "mango"];
for (let fruit of fruits) {
    console.log(fruit);   // apple, banana, mango
}

// Works on strings too
for (let char of "hello") {
    console.log(char);    // h e l l o
}
```

#### `for...in` — iterates over KEYS/PROPERTIES of an object
```js
const user = { name: "Ajay", age: 25, city: "Delhi" };
for (let key in user) {
    console.log(key, ":", user[key]);
    // name : Ajay
    // age  : 25
    // city : Delhi
}

// Also works on arrays (gives index as key — avoid this)
const arr = ["a", "b", "c"];
for (let index in arr) {
    console.log(index);   // "0" "1" "2" (string indices!)
}
```

#### `Array.forEach()` — runs a function for each element
```js
const nums = [1, 2, 3, 4];
nums.forEach((num, index) => {
    console.log(index, num);
});
// Cannot use break or continue inside forEach
```

#### `Array.map()` — loops and returns a NEW array
```js
const nums = [1, 2, 3];
const doubled = nums.map(n => n * 2);
console.log(doubled);  // [2, 4, 6]
```

#### `for...of` with `entries()` — get both index and value
```js
const fruits = ["apple", "banana", "mango"];
for (let [index, fruit] of fruits.entries()) {
    console.log(index, fruit);
    // 0 apple
    // 1 banana
    // 2 mango
}
```

---

### 8. Loop Control Statements

```js
// break — exits the loop entirely
for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
    if (i === 5) break;
    console.log(i);   // 0 1 2 3 4
}

// continue — skips current iteration, continues loop
for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
    if (i === 2) continue;
    console.log(i);   // 0 1 3 4
}
```

---

### Quick Comparison — Which Loop to Use?

| Loop | Best Used For |
|---|---|
| `for` | When you know the number of iterations |
| `while` | When condition is checked before each run |
| `do...while` | When you need at least one execution |
| `for...of` | Iterating values of arrays, strings, sets |
| `for...in` | Iterating keys/properties of objects |
| `forEach` | Running a function on each array element |
| `map` | Transforming an array into a new array |

---

### Uses of Control Flow
Control flow statements are the backbone of programming for decision-making (if/else), branching (break/continue), looping (for/while/do...while), and switching (switch statement).



